    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1977-07-05T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1977-07-05T00:00:00-05:00" n="254"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d254">
                <head>254. Memorandum From Secretary of State <persName corresp="#p_VCR_1"
                        >Vance</persName> to President <persName corresp="#p_CJE_1"
                        >Carter</persName>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d254fn1">Source: Carter Library, National
                        Security Affairs, Brzezinski Material, Subject File, Box 18, Evening Reports
                        (State): 7/77. Secret.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1977-07-05">July 5, 1977</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>[Omitted here is material unrelated to Pakistan.]</p>
                <p>5. <hi rend="italic">Pakistan.</hi> The military coup yesterday in Pakistan came
                    after talks on holding new elections had again broken down and new clashes
                    between armed, opposing political groups were reported. The military, assisted
                    by the judiciary, provides an interim administration acceptable to all political
                    parties and capable of carrying out a new national election. The cities are
                    quiet; communications and transportation are functioning normally; no Americans
                    or other foreigners have reportedly been affected. Saudi Arabia and Iran reacted
                    privately with mild relief to the military takeover.<note n="2" xml:id="d254fn2"
                        >In the left-hand margin next to this paragraph, <persName
                            corresp="#p_CJE_1">Carter</persName> wrote: “Too bad about our old
                        friend <persName corresp="#p_BZA_1">Bhutto</persName>!”</note>
                </p>
                <p>Our goals in Pakistan are first, while not commenting publicly on the coup, to
                    encourage the military authorities to honor their pledge to hold free elections
                    and, second, to continue to try to move the Pakistanis and the French toward
                    cancellation or deferral of the nuclear reprocessing plant despite the military
                    takeover.</p>
                <p>[Omitted here is material unrelated to Pakistan.]</p>
            </div>
